    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-09-16T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-09-16T04:00:00-05:00" n="804"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d804">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">794.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/9–1654:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 804<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName corresp="#p_AJM1"
                            type="from">Allison</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-09-16T18:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 16, 1954—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>644. Re <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 551.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d804fn1">
                        <ref target="#d800">Document 800</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Breakdown defense budget cut submitted by Japanese Embassy substantially
                        accurate. Detailed <gloss target="#t_NDA1">NDA</gloss>, budget figures
                        recently obtained through unofficial channels also indicate cut of 5.7
                        percent in 78.8 billion yen figure. Cut more severe if calculated on basis
                        original budget approved by Diet—81.4 billion yen of which Finance Ministry
                        allocated only 78.8 billion yen.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_MAAG1">MAAG</gloss> believes budget cut will seriously
                        hurt morale and training effectiveness defense forces, specifically <list>
                            <label>(1)</label>
                            <item>Activation of units and induction of personnel will be postponed
                                as long as possible;</item>
                            <label>(2)</label>
                            <item>26 percent cut in <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> and 17
                                percent cut in training funds in addition to other cuts in funds for
                                transportation will drastically reduce troop movements, training
                                exercises despite major need for platoon to division
                                training;</item>
                            <label>(3)</label>
                            <item>Stock levels already inadequate will be further reduced (many
                                vehicles presently inoperative due to shortage spare parts);</item>
                            <label>(4)</label>
                            <item>Construction and shipbuilding both cut 10 percent despite
                                inadequacies of present facilities and need for naval
                                vessels;</item>
                            <label>(5)</label>
                            <item>Fuel cut 11.6 percent with every prospect troops moving to
                                Hokkaido will have totally inadequate heating facilities. In effect,
                                while budget cuts will not effect projected force levels of end of
                                    <gloss target="#t_JFY1">JFY</gloss> 1954, except for Navy,
                                effectiveness and quality of Armed Forces materially reduced.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Explanation of cuts on grounds 9.3 percent price level decline not
                        considered valid. Most recent wholesale price index indicates price decline
                        only 7 percent.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>With respect to disposition of savings, Japanese Government has authority
                        with approval Finance Minister and Prime Minister <pb facs="0673" n="1729"
                            xml:id="pg_1729"/> to shift funds to procurement additional defense
                        items. However, present indications are government will not utilize
                        authority.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Foreign Office has delayed making formal approach to Embassy on budget cut
                        ostensibly on ground details not yet available for presentation. Foreign
                        Office apparently embarrassed by failure recall provisions <persName
                            corresp="#p_AJM1">Allison</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_OK1"
                            >Okazaki</persName> letters of April 6 and seek US consent prior to
                        cutting defense budget.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AJM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Allison</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
